x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">On Monday morning, =
MSNBC=E2=80=99s connubial co-hosts <b>Joe Scarborough </b>and <b>Mika Brzez=
inski</b> informed their loyal audience of almost a million viewers that th=
ey had recently ventured south from their home in Jupiter to Mar-a-Lago. Th=
ere, for the first time in seven years, they met with <b>Donald Trump</b>=
=E2=80=94the very man they=E2=80=99d spent the last <i>several years </i>vo=
ciferously pillorying. Reading from their respective teleprompters with wel=
l-choreographed solemnity, the couple conveyed this relatively benign news =
as though they were disclosing their involvement in a top-secret nuclear ne=
gotiation. Or, as CNN=E2=80=99s <b>John Berman </b>cheekily put it over on =
the rival network, =E2=80=9Cas if it were the Yalta summit.=E2=80=9D<br/><b=
r/>Anticipating some blowback from their mostly liberal coalition, Joe and =
Mika cast the Trump meeting as an attempt to foster a
constructive dialogue. =E2=80=9CFor those asking why we would go speak to t=
he president-elect during such fraught times, especially between us, I gues=
s I would ask back, =E2=80=98Why wouldn=E2=80=99t we?=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Mik=
a said. =E2=80=9CJoe and I realized it=E2=80=99s time to do something diffe=
rent, and that starts with not only talking about Donald Trump, but also ta=
lking <i>with</i> him.=E2=80=9D Later, Mika also alluded to her father, <b>=
Zbigniew</b> <b>Brzezinski</b>, a top U.S. diplomat who served as <b>Jimmy =
Carter</b>=E2=80=99s national security advisor. She explained that maintain=
ing an open dialogue was =E2=80=9Ca task shared by reporters and commentato=
rs alike.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>In light of Joe and Mika=E2=80=99s relatively e=
xalted status in the legacy media firmament, the disclosure became a minor =
source of fascination or frustration among their peers at 30 Rock, as well =
as fodder for the media=E2=80=99s broader introspective post-election soul-=
searching journey. At MSNBC, weekend host <b>Katie Phang </b>wrote that =E2=
=80=9Cnormalizing Trump
is a bad idea. Period,=E2=80=9D while <b>Stephanie Ruhle </b>sought to conv=
ince her viewers that engagement was sound journalistic practice, and by no=
 means a capitulation. Joe and Mika=E2=80=99s pilgrimage earned write-ups f=
rom the <i>Times</i>, the <i>Journal</i>, CNN, and so forth. It also induce=
d predictable hysterics from the chronically outraged gasbag class, includi=
ng <b>Keith Olbermann </b>and <b>Megyn Kelly</b>. Meanwhile, the <i>Morning=
 Joe </i>audience, already at a post-election nadir, dropped 17 percent in =
the hour after Joe and Mika revealed their Trump meeting. The following day=
, the show=E2=80=99s ratings were down <i>38 percent</i> from this year=E2=
=80=99s average.<br/><br/>Alas, the debate over statecraft vs. surrender di=
verted attention from the <i>real</i> palace intrigue. After all, Joe and M=
ika=E2=80=99s paeans to diplomacy belied the true motivation for their visi=
t to Mar-a-Lago. In fact, the couple made the trek to Palm Beach because th=
ey feared retribution, a fact that has thus
far only been alluded to by CNN=E2=80=99s <b>Brian Stelter</b>. This week, =
sources with direct knowledge of Joe and Mika=E2=80=99s thinking provided m=
e with more details on those fears that, in addition to underscoring the ba=
tshit-crazy nature of this moment in American politics, also offer insight =
into the potential chilling effect that Trump=E2=80=99s return to the Oval =
Office might have on the news media writ large, and especially MSNBC.<br/><=
br/>Since Trump=E2=80=99s victory on November 5, Joe and Mika have privatel=
y told friends that they=E2=80=99re worried the incoming president will see=
k revenge for their criticism of him during the campaign. Those concerns be=
came far more acute last week when Trump nominated <b>Matt Gaetz </b>for at=
torney general. That same day, Trump=E2=80=99s former chief strategist <b>S=
teve Bannon </b>suggested that Gaetz would go after MSNBC for trying =E2=80=
=9Cto destroy=E2=80=9D Trump. =E2=80=9C=E2=80=8B=E2=80=8BYou try to impriso=
n Trump, you try to break Trump. He=E2=80=99s not breakable,=E2=80=9D Banno=
n said on his
podcast. =E2=80=9CYou couldn=E2=80=99t destroy him. And now he has turned o=
n you. And he=E2=80=99s put a firebrand in charge of main justice, Departme=
nt of Justice, and you=E2=80=99re going to have to live with it.=E2=80=9D<b=
r/><br/>Specifically, Joe and Mika have told friends and associates they=E2=
=80=99re afraid that Trump and Gaetz will resurrect a decades-old, totally =
bullshit, birther-level conspiracy theory about the death of <b>Lori Klausu=
tis</b>, a 28-year-old intern in Scarborough=E2=80=99s former Florida congr=
essional office who died in 2001 from complications relating to a heart con=
dition, and use it to apply legal pressure on Scarborough and otherwise mak=
e his life a living hell. The couple=E2=80=99s anxiety stems, in particular=
, from <u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1=
lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dUVEVtdU16ZDE4amRGLXdtbHI0MD0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ=
